{
  "texts": [
    "Essentially, the negative effect of climate risks or uncertainties emanate from demand-side and supply-side shocks (Batten 2018; Batten et al. 2020; Ciccarelli and Marotta 2021; Kiley 2021).",
    "Further, Kotz et al. (2022) postulate that climate change exacerbate growth such that variability of rainfall respond to economic growth non-linearly.",
    "It is demonstrated by Sheng et al. (2022) that climate risks have a detrimental impact on economic activity to a similar extent regardless of whether the risks are caused by changes in temperature growth or volatility.",
    "However, when temperature growth increases by a similar magnitude in the higher uncertainty-based regime in a nonlinear context, the volatility of temperature growth contracts economic activity roughly five times more than when temperature growth decreases by a similar amount.",
    "Donadelli et al. (2021) explore labour productivity, patent obsolescence, and capital quality in their analysis of the negative R &D expenditure effect of rising temperatures."
  ]
}